          <div class="card w-100">
            <div class="card-body text-center py-4">
              <h1 class="blue mb-3">GPU Memory Exploits</h1> <!-- (TODO: better linking title?) -->
              <p class="lead mb-3" style="text-align: justify;">
              In recent years, the so-called "AI boom" has led to the widespread deployment of GPUs. Due to their high cost, GPUs are often shared by many users, e.g. in a cloud environment. However, this sharing also demands strong security for these systems. When multiple users are sharing a GPU, that GPU becomes a potential attack vector. 
              <a href="https://gururaj-s.github.io/assets/pdf/SEC25_GPUHammer.pdf"> GPUHammer</a> illustrated that GPUs are susceptible to the Rowhammer attack phenomenon,
              but only found 8 bitflips on a single GPU, limiting the ability for a practical attack to be deployed.
              In our works, we argue that the Rowhammer threat on GPUs is far more prevalent. 
              The <b>GDDR</b> and <b>GeForge</b> teams independently discovered exploits in the memory allocators for NVIDIA GPUs, allowing a <b>full takeover</b> of CPU memory from an unprivileged GPU kernel.
              </p>
            </div>
