        <!-- Card 1: GDDR -->
        <div class="col-lg-6 col-12 d-flex">
          <div class="card w-100">
            <div class="card-body">
              <div class="container">
                <div class="row justify-content-center align-items-center">
                  <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-12">
                    <img class="img-fluid" src="img/gddrlogo.png" id="logo" alt="GDDR Logo"
                      style="max-height: 400px; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" />
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-lg-8 col-sm-12">
                    <h1 class="text-left blue">GDDR: Greatly Disturbing DRAM Rows</h1>
                    <h2 class="text-left">Cross-Component Rowhammer Attacks from Modern GPUs</h2>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <p class="card-text" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
              In this work, we provide a Rowhammer characterization of <b>25</b> GDDR6 GPUs. We develop new techniques for bypassing in-device Rowhammer mitigations, producing <b>~50x</b> more flips than previously found.
              We also discover an exploit in the default memory allocator (i.e., <i>cudaMalloc</i>) that breaks the isolation of page tables and user data on the GPU.
              We then attack a GPU <b>page table</b>, allowing a user to leverage the GPU to gain read/write access to <b>all of CPU memory</b>.
              </p>
